h a placeholder might work. However, adding ProjectBuilder could be time-consuming. I should check whether a native executable build exists.\\n\\nThe TCK likely includes dependencies, and the native image compile succeeded with minimal requirements. If I add Gradle internals, there’s a risk of failure due to unsupported features. An alternative could be testing `proguard.gradle.ProGuardTask` functionality via public class resources, but I need to figure out if the ProGuardTask exposes Maven POM metadata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting TCK Tests**\\n\\nI need to look at how TCK tests utilize libraries. It might be helpful to add a test that exercises the Gradle DSL \\\"option getters\\\" by avoiding the inspection of private configurations. Public methods get called by setters and return null. For flag methods, there aren't public observables. I wonder if I could generate config output with `printconfiguration` and then call `proguard()`? I think I need jar files for this, but I can call `proguard()` after setting `printconfiguration(file)` to write the config and exit. I'll check the bytecode of `proguard()` too.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_bjkQBn2FUZa9zmUvBRvogchb|fc_001c9f44544a01750169fe092fa2448191b80ed4be8838de53", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath tests/src/net.sf.proguard/proguard-gradle/5.2.1/build/jacoco/effective/proguard_gradle_5_2_1_jar:/home/vjovanov/.m2/repository/net/sf/proguard/proguard-base/5.2.1/proguard-base-5.2.1.jar -c -p proguard.gradle.ProGuardTask | grep -n \"proguard()\" -A180"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 629, "output": 743, "cacheRead": 31232, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32604, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778256146977, "responseId": "resp_001c9f44544a01750169fe0914a9848191b4506627e2edf200"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResul