[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Gradle integration options**\n\nI’m considering whether to create Gradle integration using the Tooling API or run a Gradle build in a subprocess. Using the public Gradle API as a plugin could work, but launching external Gradle through native tests doesn’t seem ideal. It might take over 60 seconds, and dynamic testing adds complexity. I'm also thinking about testing ProGuard functionality, but using the ProGuardTask subclass with Unsafe could contradict best practices regarding public API usage. I need to be cautious about direct reflection or serialization.\n\n**Considering Objenesis for Gradle**\n\nI'm thinking about using Objenesis, which might already be a dependency in Gradle. However, there’s the issue of not using direct reflection. While it could instantiate without a constructor, this could violate public API guidelines, especially since it relies on ProGuardTask public methods. I wonder if direct instantiation is allowed in Gradle version 2.2.1 for DefaultTask, but the classpath in my test appears to be linked to Gradle 9's DefaultTask instead.\n\n**Inspecting Gradle tasks**\n\nI’m considering whether the new ProGuardTask might work because Gradle 2’s DefaultTask probably allowed direct instantiation. That makes me want to check the DefaultTask constructor specifically. There’s definitely a chance this could be relevant since understanding the constructor could help clarify how tasks are created in Gradle 2. I’ll dive into that to see if my assumption holds up!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_001c9f44544a01750169fe0c0adda08191af6c4e729ac287b1\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_gwct5elcv9O-Jf94r6-gqVQ-KvSJIiUILHAxydTqfEk9qfvkf4oqY_GfbbtFAw_6pn98fRldSWMT_xQCC1268VfPrOSuOYrixF30uzv7N7qQ5DQxkjgSrFfAiEn9x4EftkpDI8viORXrYCsQFrdnif5k7wibKjBtDHzi9rvUtTdjClIGYM9WcnQmEtguz40P0EjmTMJIB1h6b3Wd7uKn6TA8_drkd3eEV0Fxhss1Dlpgfy