 but using Java 9 features might lead to runtime failures when running under older Gradle. The developer advises not to run full tests myself, so I might need to reconsider running tasks with an external JVM to avoid compatibility issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing compile issues**\\n\\nI'm considering whether using the current Gradle API for the subprocess classpath will help avoid native compile problems. However, I face a module opening issue that could be remedied by adding `--add-opens` to the Java subprocess. Still, including the generated gradle-api in the classpath seems tricky. Gradle 2.2 may match the library, but that could fail on Java 17+ due to version issues, as it only supports up to Java 1.9. We might need to steer clear of Gradle's ProjectBuilder altogether and focus on the current Gradle version for subprocesses.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating native image issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether the native image scans service providers could cause issues with FileSystemProviders. It seems like that might still lead to failures, so I’m hesitating on that front. I could potentially use an external Gradle 9 by creating a classpath from the Gradle installation in the test environment. That approach would mean there's no need to add gradleApi to the native image, which simplifies things quite a bit.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Gradle dependencies**\\n\\nI’m trying to avoid unnecessary dependencies while passing the `gradle.gradleHomeDir` property. I think I should include `--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED` for the Java run, but not for `javac`. I wonder if using the test classpath could help with older Gradle versions, like 2.2. It seems I should prioritize the current version's jars and manage classpath order carefully since including the old gradle-core dependencies might cause conflicts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering ProjectBuilder deprecation**\\n\\nI'm noticing that compiling against the current ProjectBuilder could lead to deprecated warnings, but that shouldn’t necessarily cause a failure. The test compile doesn't show any warnings, which is nice. I’m wondering if I should consider whether users expect no deprecated APIs. The probe source utilizes ProjectBuilder, which might be deprecated in the current context, but since we're doing external compilation, I'm thinking any warnings in the output could be worth monitoring closely.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining ProGuardTask Implementation**\\n\\nI need to ensure that the ProGuardTask class is assignable to the current Task. The JVM passed with the creation, so that’s good. I require the current Gradle classpath property. In the build.gradle file, I’ll gather the runtime classpath from the Gradle home directory and its plugins. I’ll set this up using `systemProperty` and incorporate it into runtime arguments. Additionally, I need to run Java with `--add-opens` option to prevent failures during execution.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_A2BfeIJwyglgHiIUlCyiZHv4|fc_001c9f44544a01750169fe0d230da881919d859de62aa4af97", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.sf.proguard/proguard-gradle/5.2.1/src/test/java/net_sf_proguard/proguard_gradle/Proguard_gradleTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    private static final String TEST_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY = \"proguard.gradle.test.classpath\";\n", "newText": "    private static final String TEST_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY = \"proguard.gradle.test.classpath\";\n    private static final String GRADLE_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY = \"proguard.gradle.current.classpath\";\n"}, {"oldText": "                    final ProGuardTask task = project.getTasks().create(\"minifyApplication\", ProGuardTask.class);\n", "newText": "                    final ProGuardTask task = project.getTasks().register(\"minifyApplication\", ProGuardTask.class).get();\n"}, {"oldText": "        final String testClasspath = System.getProperty(TEST_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY);\n        assertThat(testClasspath).isNotBlank();\n", "newText": "        final String testClasspath = System.getProperty(TEST_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY);\n        final String gradleClasspath = System.getProperty(GRADLE_CLASSPATH_PROPERTY);\n        assertThat(testClasspath).isNotBlank();\n        assertThat(gradleClasspath).isNotBlank();\n        final String probeClasspath = gradleClasspath + System.getProperty(\"path.separator\") + testClasspath;\n"}, {"oldText": "        runProcess(List.of(javaExecutable(\"javac\"), \"-classpath\", testClasspath,\n", "newText": "        runProcess(List.of(javaExecutable(\"javac\"), \"-classpath\", probeClasspath,\n"}, {"oldText": "        runProcess(List.of(javaExecutable(\"java\"), \"-classpath\",\n                classesDirectory + System.getProperty(\"path.separator\") + testClasspath,\n                \"ProGuardTaskDslProbe\"), \"run probe\");\n", "newText": "        runProcess(List.of(javaExecutable(\"java\"), \"--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED\", \"-classpath\",\n                classesDirectory + System.getProperty(\"path.separator\") + probeClasspath,\n                \"ProGuardTaskDslProbe\"), \"run probe\");\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 540, "output": 2166, "cacheRead": 96768, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 99474, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778257152826, "responseId": "resp_001c9f44544a01750169fe0d04968c8191a8b6c97a78be229a"}}
